      "content": "hey im studying for my data science midterm and im a bit stuck on regularization. can u explain the main difference between L1 and L2 regularization specifically in terms of what they do to the model coefficients?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! L1 and L2 regularization are two common techniques used to prevent overfitting in machine learning models. L1 regularization, also known as Lasso, adds a penalty equal to the absolute value of the magnitude of the coefficients to the loss function. This can lead to some coefficients being shrunk to zero, effectively performing feature selection. On the other hand, L2 regularization, also known as Ridge, adds a penalty equal to the square of the magnitude of the coefficients. This tends to shrink the coefficients towards zero but rarely exactly to zero, which can help to reduce the variance without necessarily eliminating any features. In essence, L1 can help you pick a simpler model by reducing the number of features, while L2 helps to improve the model's performance by keeping all features but reducing their impact.",
